<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-107-874  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 107 874.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Telephony  March 13 1989 v216 n11 p29(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Loop carrier systems of the 1990s: digital or optical? (includesrelated article on roadblocks to optical systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Negrin, Alan E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber optics will be the loop technology of the 1990s, and fiberwill progress from deployment in feeder plants toward end-to-endloop connectivity.andP;  Fiber's main appeal to both customers andtelephone companies is its ability to provide new services.andP;  Otheradvantages of fiber over copper include its lower maintenancecosts, absence of crosstalk and immunity from electrical surges.andO;The main obstacles that still must be overcome before the fiberoptical loop network of the 1990s can be built include the lack oftransmission and format standards, the problem of competingtransport offerings by both local exchange carriers and CATVproviders, and the feeder technology necessary to make thesubscriber network of the 1990s fully optical fiber.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Digital Loop CarrierOptical communicationsComparisonTelecommunications.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Loop technology network progression. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>